    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-05-14T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-05-14T02:00:00-05:00" n="25"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d25">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.5/5–1452: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 25<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Republic of China (<persName
                            corresp="#p_JHP1" type="from">Jones</persName>)</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d25fn1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_JHP1">Howard P. Jones</persName>, Counselor of Embassy
                        at Taipei, was in charge of the Embassy in the absence of <persName
                            corresp="#p_RKL1">Karl Rankin</persName>, who was away May 11–Oct. 1 for
                        consultations in Washington and home leave. <persName corresp="#p_RKL1"
                            >Rankin</persName>’s account of his discussions with President <persName
                            corresp="#p_THS1">Truman</persName> and other officials during this trip
                        may be found in <persName corresp="#p_RKL1">Karl Lott Rankin</persName>, <hi
                            rend="italic">China Assignment</hi> (Seattle, University of Washington
                        Press, 1964), pp. 138–149.</note>
                    <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Taipei</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-05-14T16:00:00+09:00"
                            >May 14, 1952—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1439. Substance <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 813, May 9 communicated
                    to <gloss target="#t_FonMin1">FonMin</gloss> who was grateful confirmation
                    assumed US position but made following observations.</p>
                <p>While Chinese Govt forces will of course defend islands in question Chinese
                    Commie capabilities were such as to enable capture islands any time willing
                    commit sufficient forces for purpose. Since Chi Govt without active support
                    Seventh Fleet wld find it impossible maintain successful defense in face
                    determined, well-mounted attacks. In this connection <gloss target="#t_FonMin1"
                        >FonMin</gloss> raised again, without expecting answer, repeatedly discussed
                    question as to what constitutes defense Formosa and at what point Chinese Commie
                    threat would be taken seriously enough warrant involvement Seventh Fleet. Seems
                    clear he was implying serious attack on islands as distinguished <pb facs="0079"
                        n="51" xml:id="pg_51"/> from hit and run tactics should be considered as
                    preliminary to invasion Formosa.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_JHP1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Jones</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
